Da Vinci's Vatruvian man can also be referenced back to history alhough it in itself is in history now.  This piece is based on notes for Vatruvius' devine proporion scale.  The diagram shows the perfect proportions for a person to be.
<br>
<br>
<center><i>The Vatruvian Man.</i></center>
<center><img src="http://imgc.allpostersimages.com/images/P-473-488-90/7/799/69KI000Z/posters/leonardo-da-vinci-vitruvian-man-proportions-of-the-human-figure.jpg" style="width:304px;height:410px"></center>

This is a key point in history where scale and proportion became important.  You can see the comparison between the thought for scale put into this piece and neandarthol art.

The Vatruvian man follows The Golden Ratio.  The Golden Ratio is a scale used within design.  It explores the appearence of Phi (1.618).  The Fibbinacci sequence is a mathematical design.  The number can be found by adding the two numbers before it.  The Golden Ratio is created by using these numbers in a spiral.

<br>
<br>
<center><i>The Fibbonaci Sequence.</i></center>
<center><img src="http://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/fibonacci-spiral.gif" style="width:304px;height:240px"></center>

The Golden Ratio has been used by many influential artists and was used in abundance by Da Vinci.
<br>
<br>

<center><i>The Mona Lisa.</i></center>
<center><img src="http://thewonderofphibykevinandashley.weebly.com/uploads/1/4/4/6/14467032/453423.jpg?0" style="width:304px;height:450px"></center>
