Week Three

The 1900's are the century of change for art and design.  Art movements dominated the 20th century and technology grew at such an unbelivably rapid pace,  From the invention of the photograph to the moving image to the telephone to light bulb.  The first photograph was taken by Joseph Nicephore Niepce and was a photograph of some buildings he had taken from his window.
<br>
<br>
<center><i>The First Photograph</i></center>
<center><img src="http://www.theasc.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/3.-800pxView_from_the_Window_at_Le_Gras_Joseph_Nic%C3%A9phore_Ni%C3%A9pce.jpeg" style="width:304px;height:300px"></center>
<br>
<br>
A little further on from this Louis Daguerre was using light sensitive Iodine.  A famous photo of his is the Boulevard du Temple in 1838.
<br>
<br>
<center><i>Boulevard du Temple</i></center>
<center><img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d3/Boulevard_du_Temple_by_Daguerre.jpg" style="width:304px;height:300px"></center>
<br>
<br>Matthew Brady was  very famous 19th century photographer and was known as the 'Father of Photojournalism'.  His images mainly consisted of celebrities and war.  This made him almost the inventor of paraparazzi.
<br>
<br>
<center><i>President Abraham Lincoln</i></center>
<center><img src="http://i.dailymail.co.uk/i/pix/2013/08/06/article-2385208-1B28911A000005DC-155_964x948.jpg" style="width:304px;height:300px"></center>
<br>
<br>
<center><i>The Battle of Gettysburg</i></center>
<center><img src="http://www.ourworldmyeye.com/wp-content/uploaads/Mathew-Brady-Battle-of-Gettysburg.jpg" style="width:304px;height:300px"></center>

Roger Fenton also took war photography and has some iconic images of the civil war.  Other artists have taken influence such as Paul Seawright and attempted to recreate this start feeling of death with a modern approach.

<br>
<br>
<center><i>Roger Fenton</i></center>
<center><img src="http://images.tate.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/grid-normal-8-cols/public/images/roger_fenton_valley_of_shadow_of_death.jpg?itok=Q0U7nPIk" style="width:304px;height:300px"></center>
